Sandra Day O'Connor, the first woman on the US Supreme Court, announced her retirement, allowing President George W. Bush to shape the court's ideological balance.
Bush vowed to select a nominee promptly, sparking a potential Senate confirmation battle.
Political groups mobilized for the fight, with conservatives eyeing the chance to overturn Roe v. Wade.
Speculation surrounded potential candidates like Alberto Gonzales.
The NAACP urged a civil rights advocate for the position.
Amidst the political turmoil, Bush emphasized a commitment to selecting justices who interpret the Constitution strictly.
The retirement of O'Connor marks a pivotal moment in reshaping the nation's highest court.
